

What is the Flyweight Design Pattern?
..................................................................
The Flyweight Pattern is a Structural Design Pattern used to reduce memory usage by sharing common objects instead of creating new ones repeatedly.

Definition: The Flyweight Pattern shares objects that have the same state, minimizing memory consumption and improving performance.

Why Do We Need Flyweight?
..................................................................
Suppose a banking application displays 10,000 customer accounts.

Without Flyweight:
..................................................................
Customer 1 → Bank Logo
Customer 2 → Bank Logo
Customer 3 → Bank Logo
...
Customer 10000 → Bank Logo

The application creates 10,000 Bank Logo objects, wasting memory.

With Flyweight:
..................................................................
                Bank Logo
                    ▲
      ┌─────────────┼─────────────┐
      │             │             │
Customer1      Customer2     Customer10000

Only one Bank Logo object is shared by all customers.

Real-Time Banking Example
..................................................................
Suppose every ATM screen displays the same:

Bank Logo
Bank Name
Theme

Instead of creating these objects for every ATM session, create them once and share them.
..................................................................
Step 1: Flyweight Interface
..................................................................
public interface BankLogo {

    void display(String branchName);
}

Step 2: Concrete Flyweight
..................................................................
public class SBIBankLogo implements BankLogo {

    public SBIBankLogo() {
        System.out.println("Creating Bank Logo...");
    }

    @Override
    public void display(String branchName) {

        System.out.println(
                "Displaying SBI Logo for " + branchName);
    }
}

Step 3: Flyweight Factory
..................................................................
import java.util.HashMap;
import java.util.Map;

public class BankLogoFactory {

    private static Map<String, BankLogo> map = new HashMap<>();

    public static BankLogo getLogo(String bank) {

        if (!map.containsKey(bank)) {

            map.put(bank, new SBIBankLogo());
        }

        return map.get(bank);
    }
}

Step 4: Client
..................................................................
public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        BankLogo logo1 =
                BankLogoFactory.getLogo("SBI");

        logo1.display("Hyderabad");

        BankLogo logo2 =
                BankLogoFactory.getLogo("SBI");

        logo2.display("Chennai");

        System.out.println(logo1 == logo2);
    }
}

Output
..................................................................
Creating Bank Logo...

Displaying SBI Logo for Hyderabad

Displaying SBI Logo for Chennai

true

Notice:

Creating Bank Logo...

appears only once.

