Intrinsic vs Extrinsic State
Intrinsic State (Shared)

Stored inside the Flyweight object.

Example:
..................................................................
Bank Logo
Bank Name
Logo Color

These values are common for everyone.

Extrinsic State (Not Shared)

Passed by the client.

Example:
..................................................................
Branch Name
Customer Name
Account Number

These values are different for each request.

Example:

logo.display("Hyderabad");

Here:

Hyderabad

is the extrinsic state.

Another Real-Time Example
Text Editor (MS Word)

Suppose a document contains:

AAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAAA

Without Flyweight:

20 Character Objects

With Flyweight:

One Character Object

↓

Used 20 Times

Memory usage is reduced.

Java Examples

The Flyweight pattern is used in:

String Constant Pool
Integer Cache (Integer.valueOf())
Font objects
Icons
Image caching

Example:

String s1 = "Java";
String s2 = "Java";

System.out.println(s1 == s2);

Output

true

Both references point to the same object in the String pool.

Advantages
..................................................................
Reduces memory usage.
Improves performance.
Avoids duplicate objects.
Ideal when many similar objects are created.

Disadvantages
..................................................................
Increases design complexity.
Requires separating intrinsic and extrinsic state correctly.


